#X text 461 77 "counter" is simply an object that counts. It can count
up \, count down and count up and then down. Where it starts and where
it stops are all definable. Note this is the default PD-extended counter
\, there are other counters that work differently.;
#X text 641 173 lower;
#X text 681 213 upper;
#X text 661 193 set;
#X text 461 314 The first argument for counter is the direction in
which to count. "0" means forward \, "1" means backward and "2" means
forward and then backward. The second is the lower limit (number to
start counting at). The third is the upper limit to count to. The right
most inlet is the upper limit. The second right most inlet sets the
current counter value. The third right most inlet is the lower limit.
The fourth right most inlet is the direction.;
#X text 21 187 You can turn a Metro on and off by sending it a "1"
or "0" message. Because a toggle sends 0/1 messages \, we can simply
connect it directly. Metro also accepts an argument (words or numbers
written after the object name). This argument is how fast the metro
should send out bangs (in milliseconds). You can always change the
speed of the metro by sending it number messages through the rightmost
inlet.;
